# Tools for developing hypotheses

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
Developing hypotheses is a crucial step in the social innovation process, and this tool helps simplify how we communicate expected impact.

## Purpose
This method is used to develop and express theories of change in ways that can easily move us toward experimentation, helping to isolate specific phenomena or variables where an experimental intervention can be designed.

## How it works
The tool involves defining a hypothesis in if/then fashion, listing variables, and creating a causal chain with independent and dependent variables. Intermediary causes/effects and conditional variables are then added to the chain.

## Requirements
Understanding of causal inference is necessary to effectively use this tool for R&D purposes.

## Reflections
Simplifying how we develop and express theories of change in ways that can easily move us toward experimentation is key, but be aware of potential oversimplification if the bigger picture is lost or variables are left out.

## Related methods (if any)
This tool is used with Horizon Scanning and Explore methods.
